## 1. Load and clean cleavable XL-MS crosslinks

**Input:** Annika 2.0 crosslink report at the peptide-pair level.  
**Output:** `rawdf`, a cleaned peptide-level table with normalized accessions, simplified protein descriptions, and an `MS = "cleaved"` label.

```{r load-clean-annika}
# Read the Annika 2.0 peptide-pair crosslink report.
rawdf <- read.table("TachyAll_XL_publication_20240916_Crosslinks.txt", header = TRUE, sep = "\t")

# Normalize protein accessions by removing analysis-specific suffixes and isoform IDs.
# This keeps downstream joins stable across Annika, ToxoDB, STRING, and visualization exports.
rawdf <- rawdf %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.character), ~str_replace_all(., "-t26_1-p1", ""))) %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.character), ~str_replace_all(., "\\.P\\d{2,4}", "")))%>% #remove isoform
  #remove unnecessary columns
  #select(-c(Crosslinks., Checked, Crosslinker, Number.of.Proteins,)) %>%
  mutate(MS = "cleaved") #add MS method as cleaved

# Simplify protein description fields so exported tables are easier to read.
#
# clean_gene_product()
#   - Handles transcript-style pipe-delimited annotations by extracting the gene-product field.
#   - Removes common annotation prefixes that add length but little information.
#   - Operates only on the columns supplied in `columns`.
clean_gene_product <- function(data, columns) {
  # Apply multiple transformations within mutate across the specified columns
  data %>% 
    mutate(across(all_of(columns), ~if_else(
      str_starts(., "transcript"),  # Check if starts with "transcript"
      str_split(., "\\|", simplify = TRUE)[, 4],  # Split and select the 4th element if condition is met
      .  # Keep the original value if condition is not met
    ))) %>%
    mutate(across(all_of(columns), ~str_remove(., "^\\s*gene_product="))) %>%  # Remove the "gene_product=" prefix
    mutate(across(all_of(columns), ~str_remove(., "dense granule protein "))) %>%  # Remove "dense granule protein " prefix
    mutate(across(all_of(columns), ~str_remove(., "ribosomal protein "))) %>%  # Remove "ribosomal protein " prefix
    mutate(across(all_of(columns), ~str_remove(., "SAG-related sequence "))) %>%  # Remove "SAG-related sequence
    mutate(across(all_of(columns), ~str_remove(., "heat shock protein ")))  # Remove "heat shock protein " prefix
}

# Apply the description-cleaning helper to both Annika protein-description columns.
rawdf <- clean_gene_product(rawdf, c("Protein.Descriptions.A", "Protein.Descriptions.B"))
```
## 2. Resolve ambiguous protein assignments

Some spectra map to multiple possible proteins. Two strategies are shown below:

1. **Strict filtering:** remove ambiguous rows entirely.
2. **RNA-seq prioritization:** split ambiguous rows and keep the candidate with the highest tachyzoite RNA-seq abundance.

The downstream workflow uses the RNA-seq-prioritized version assigned to `rawdf2`.

### 2.1 Strict option: remove ambiguous accessions
```{r}
# Remove peptide pairs where either side maps to multiple proteins separated by semicolons.
rawdf2 <- rawdf %>% filter(!str_detect(Accession.A, ";") & !str_detect(Accession.B, ";"))
```

### 2.2 Preferred option: resolve ambiguity by tachyzoite RNA-seq abundance
```{r}
# Load the RNA-seq feature table. The feature-table construction section later in this notebook
# explains how `ToxoDB67_AllFeature_woSTRING.txt` is generated.
RnaSeqDF <- read.table(file = "ToxoDB67_AllFeature_woSTRING.txt", sep = "\t", header = TRUE) %>%
  select(Gene_ID, RnaSeq)

rawdf2 <- rawdf %>%
  # Mark which peptide side contains an ambiguous protein assignment.
  mutate(
    Ambiguous = case_when(
      str_detect(Accession.A, ";") ~ "A",  # Label A if Accession.A contains ";"
      str_detect(Accession.B, ";") ~ "B",  # Label B if Accession.B contains ";"
      TRUE ~ "False"  # All other cases
    )) %>%
  separate_rows(Accession.A, In.protein.A, sep = ";") %>% # Split multiple candidate proteins for peptide A into separate rows.
  mutate(Accession.A = str_trim(Accession.A)) %>% # Remove leading/trailing whitespace introduced by semicolon splitting.
  left_join(RnaSeqDF, by = c("Accession.A" = "Gene_ID")) %>%
  group_by(Crosslinks.Peptide.Group.ID) %>% # Group by the original Annika peptide-group identifier so only one candidate is retained.
  arrange(desc(RnaSeq), In.protein.A) %>%  # Sort by RNA-seq abundance; use the residue position as a deterministic tie-breaker.
  slice_head(n = 1) %>% # Keep the highest-abundance candidate for each original peptide group.
  select(-RnaSeq) %>% # Drop the temporary RNA-seq column after ranking.
  ungroup() %>%
  # Repeat the same ambiguity-resolution process for peptide B.
  separate_rows(Accession.B, In.protein.B, sep = ";") %>% #split multiple observations in peptide B
  mutate(Accession.B = str_trim(Accession.B)) %>% # Remove leading/trailing whitespace introduced by semicolon splitting.
  left_join(RnaSeqDF, by = c("Accession.B" = "Gene_ID")) %>%
  group_by(Crosslinks.Peptide.Group.ID) %>% # Group by the original Annika peptide-group identifier so only one candidate is retained.
  arrange(desc(RnaSeq), In.protein.B) %>%  # Sort by RNA-seq abundance; use the residue position as a deterministic tie-breaker.
  slice_head(n = 1) %>%  # Keep the highest-abundance candidate for each original peptide group.
  select(-RnaSeq) %>% # Drop the temporary RNA-seq column after ranking.
  ungroup()
```

## 3. Collapse peptide-level records to residue-residue interactions (RRIs)

This section converts peptide-pair observations into unique residue-residue interactions. RRIs are the main unit for structural mapping because each RRI identifies two protein residues.

**Key operations:**

- Classify target/decoy status as TT, TD, or DD for FDR estimation.
- Assign unique placeholder IDs to decoy entries with missing accessions so decoys do not collapse into one artificial RRI.
- Build a sorted `RRI` key so A-B and B-A observations are treated as the same interaction.
- Aggregate CSM counts and combine scores using a Euclidean norm.

```{r rri-condensation}
RRIdf <- rawdf2 %>%
  # Add a Decoy.Pair label used for target-decoy FDR calculation:
# TT = target-target, TD = target-decoy, DD = decoy-decoy.
  rowwise() %>%
  mutate(
    Decoy.Pair = case_when(
      # both Accession.A and Accession.B are empty or NA
      (is.na(Accession.A) | Accession.A == "") &
      (is.na(Accession.B) | Accession.B == "") ~ "DD",
      
      # exactly one of them is empty/NA → “TD”
      (is.na(Accession.A) | Accession.A == "") &
      !(is.na(Accession.B) | Accession.B == "") ~ "TD",
      
      !(is.na(Accession.A) | Accession.A == "") &
      (is.na(Accession.B) | Accession.B == "") ~ "TD",
      
      # if neither is empty/NA → “TT”
      TRUE ~ "TT"
    )
  ) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  # Give each blank decoy accession a unique placeholder ID.
# Without this, all missing decoys would collapse into the same artificial interaction.
  # 1) Tag every row/column for “is empty?”
  mutate(
    is_empty_A = is.na(Accession.A) | Accession.A == "",
    is_empty_B = is.na(Accession.B) | Accession.B == ""
  ) %>%
   # 2) Compute total number of empty cells across A+B (same for every row)
  mutate(total_empty = sum(is_empty_A) + sum(is_empty_B)) %>%
  
  # 3) Generate exactly `total_empty` unique 6-digit random numbers, 
  #    zero-pad them, and prepend “DECOY_”; store as a list-column `all_decoys`
  mutate(all_decoys = list(
    str_c(
      "DECOY_",
      str_pad(
        sample(0:999999, size = total_empty[1], replace = FALSE),
        width = 6,
        pad = "0"
      )
    )
  )) %>%
  
  # 4) Assign a row-wise index for each empty spot in A and B:
  #    - “index_A” runs 1, 2, … across all rows where is_empty_A == TRUE
  #    - “index_B” runs (1 + #empty_A), (2 + #empty_A), … across rows where is_empty_B == TRUE
  mutate(
    # Within all rows, do a running count of TRUEs in is_empty_A
    index_A = if_else(is_empty_A, cumsum(is_empty_A), NA_integer_),
    # For B, offset its cumsum by sum(is_empty_A) so IDs don’t collide
    index_B = if_else(is_empty_B, cumsum(is_empty_B) + sum(is_empty_A), NA_integer_)
  ) %>%
  
  # 5) Now pull from the “all_decoys” vector to fill each empty cell:
  mutate(
    Accession.A = if_else(
      is_empty_A,
      # pick the index-th decoy from all_decoys[[1]]
      all_decoys[[1]][index_A],
      Accession.A
    ),
    Accession.B = if_else(
      is_empty_B,
      all_decoys[[1]][index_B],
      Accession.B
    )
  ) %>%
  
  # 6) Drop all helper columns
  select(-is_empty_A, -is_empty_B, -total_empty, -all_decoys, -index_A, -index_B) %>%
  
  # Fill missing decoy residue positions with 0 so RRI labels can be constructed.
    mutate(across(
    c(In.protein.A, In.protein.B),
    ~ if_else(is.na(.) | . == "", "0", .)
  )) %>%
  mutate(across(c(In.protein.A, In.protein.B), as.numeric)) %>%

  # Create a direction-independent Residue-to-Residue Interaction (RRI) label.
  rowwise() %>%
  mutate(
    RRI = {
      # Build the two `protein:position` strings on the fly.
      R1 <- str_c(Accession.A, In.protein.A, sep = ":")
      R2 <- str_c(Accession.B, In.protein.B, sep = ":")
      # Sort the two residue identifiers so reciprocal observations collapse together.
      paste(sort(c(R1, R2)), collapse = "-")
    }
  ) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  
  # Aggregate all peptide-level entries that share the same RRI.
  group_by(RRI) %>%
  mutate(
    Number.of.CSMs = sum(Number.of.CSMs),  # replace by group sum
    RRI.Score = sqrt(sum(Best.CSM.Score^2)) # Combine evidence by Euclidean norm of the best CSM scores.
  ) %>%
  slice_max(order_by = Best.CSM.Score, n = 1, with_ties = FALSE) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  
  # Create a direction-independent Protein-to-Protein Interaction (PPI) label.
  rowwise() %>%
  mutate(
    PPI = paste(sort(c(Accession.A, Accession.B)), collapse = "-")
  ) %>%
  ungroup()
```
## 4. Collapse RRIs to protein-protein interactions (PPIs)

PPI rows summarize all RRIs connecting the same protein pair. These rows are used for interactome analysis, Cytoscape visualization, and machine-learning features.

```{r ppi-condensation}
PPIdf <- RRIdf %>%
  # Aggregate all RRI-level evidence for each PPI.
  group_by(PPI) %>%
  mutate(
    number_unique_RR  = n(),                              # count how many RRI rows are in this PPI group
    Number.of.CSMs  = sum(Number.of.CSMs),               # sum CSMs over all RRIs in the group
    PPI.Score       = sqrt(sum(RRI.Score^2))             # Euclidean‐norm of all RRI.Score in this PPI
  ) %>%
  slice_max(order_by = RRI.Score, n = 1, with_ties = FALSE) %>%
  ungroup()
```


## 5. Estimate FDR-derived score cutoffs

FDR is estimated after sorting inter-protein links from highest to lowest score. The formula used here is:

`FDR = (cumulative TD - cumulative DD) / cumulative TT`

Intra-protein links are excluded from this target-decoy cutoff calculation.

### 5.1 RRI-level FDR cutoffs
```{r}
RRIfdrcalc <- RRIdf %>%
  filter(Crosslink.Type == "Inter") %>%
  # Sort from highest to lowest score before computing cumulative target/decoy counts.
  arrange(desc(RRI.Score)) %>%
  # Add cumulative target-decoy counts and calculate the running FDR estimate.
  mutate(
    CumTD = cumsum(Decoy.Pair == "TD"),
    CumDD = cumsum(Decoy.Pair == "DD"),
    CumTT = cumsum(Decoy.Pair == "TT"),
    RRI_FDR = (CumTD - CumDD)/CumTT)

desired_FDRs <- c(0.01, 0.05, 0.10, 0.30, 0.50)

cutoff_table_RRI <- tibble(FDR_target = desired_FDRs) %>%
  mutate(
    cutoff_score = map_dbl(FDR_target, ~ {
      tmp <- RRIfdrcalc %>%
        filter(RRI_FDR <= .x)
      if (nrow(tmp) == 0) {
        # no row ever achieves FDR <= .x → return NA
        NA_real_
      } else {
        # take the bottommost (lowest‐score) row among those that pass
        tmp %>%
          slice_tail(n = 1) %>%
          pull(RRI.Score)
      }
    })
  )

cutoff_table_RRI

```



### 5.2 PPI-level FDR cutoffs
```{r}
PPIfdrcalc <- PPIdf %>%
  filter(Crosslink.Type == "Inter") %>%
  # Sort from highest to lowest score before computing cumulative target/decoy counts.
  arrange(desc(PPI.Score)) %>%
  # Add cumulative target-decoy counts and calculate the running FDR estimate.
  mutate(
    CumTD = cumsum(Decoy.Pair == "TD"),
    CumDD = cumsum(Decoy.Pair == "DD"),
    CumTT = cumsum(Decoy.Pair == "TT"),
    PPI_FDR = (CumTD - CumDD)/CumTT)

desired_FDRs <- c(0.01, 0.05, 0.10, 0.30, 0.50)

cutoff_table_PPI <- tibble(FDR_target = desired_FDRs) %>%
  mutate(
    cutoff_score = map_dbl(FDR_target, ~ {
      tmp <- PPIfdrcalc %>%
        filter(PPI_FDR <= .x)
